Until this week’s stock market swoon, the inevitable economic toll had gotten lost in the panicked coverage of the virus’s spread.
Roughly 28 million Americans lack health insurance.
With this outbreak, not only does the moral imperative for universal health care grow, but so does the pragmatic rationale: Germs don’t obey class and ethnic and national boundaries.
And right now, there’s an unprecedented need to expand the health care umbrella to everyone who lives in the United States.
With this outbreak, not only does the moral imperative for universal health care grow, but so does the pragmatic rationale.